679
00:47:34,718 --> 00:47:37,016
<i>Oh, I'm flattered. Thank you for approving.</i>

680
00:47:37,087 --> 00:47:38,850
<i>You're very welcome.</i>

681
00:47:42,192 --> 00:47:44,752
Right. Well. Should we hit the sack?

682
00:47:45,395 --> 00:47:46,919
Sorry. I guess I...

683
00:47:49,032 --> 00:47:54,402
<i>Well, as much as I'd love to sit here
and drink the whole bottle of Caparzo...</i>

684
00:47:54,805 --> 00:47:57,831
No, go to bed. You should.
Good night, Charlie.

685
00:47:59,209 --> 00:48:00,403
Right.

686
00:48:00,777 --> 00:48:02,904
- Well, good night.
- Good night.

687
00:48:12,689 --> 00:48:15,180
Forgive me. Where are my manners?

688
00:48:15,259 --> 00:48:18,023
<i>You know, I've been wondering that
since I met you.</i>

689
00:48:18,095 --> 00:48:20,461
<i>Yes, well, I don't know what it is,</i>

690
00:48:21,164 --> 00:48:23,564
but you seem to bring out
the very worst in me.

691
00:48:24,134 --> 00:48:26,602
<i>- Somehow it's my fault.
- All of this is your fault.</i>

692
00:48:26,670 --> 00:48:28,900
You wrote that blasted letter.

693
00:48:30,908 --> 00:48:33,741
Nonetheless, may I walk you to your room?

694
00:48:34,544 --> 00:48:37,206
<i>You know, I'm not the buttoned-up,</i>

695
00:48:37,281 --> 00:48:39,806
buttock-clenching killjoy
you try to make me out as.

696
00:48:39,883 --> 00:48:43,944
Right. And I made you argue that
true love is bollocks.

697
00:48:45,389 --> 00:48:46,583
Guilty.

698
00:48:49,593 --> 00:48:52,619
<i>It's just that I'm genuinely worried for her.</i>

699
00:48:53,430 --> 00:48:55,762
I know she may seem carefree,

700
00:48:57,434 --> 00:49:00,232
<i>but her life hasn't been all that simple.</i>

701
00:49:02,272 --> 00:49:04,502
Is it that unreasonable for me to worry?

702
00:49:04,574 --> 00:49:08,510
<i>No, but I have a really good feeling
about this. You'll see.</i>

703
00:49:08,979 --> 00:49:10,913
<i>Let's hope you're right.</i>

704
00:49:34,004 --> 00:49:35,471
<i>NURSE: Signora Claire.</i>

705
00:49:36,373 --> 00:49:37,704
(SPEAKING ITALIAN)

706
00:49:38,575 --> 00:49:40,202
<i>Signor Bartolini.</i>

707
00:49:41,511 --> 00:49:43,411
(SPEAKING ITALIAN)

708
00:49:47,918 --> 00:49:49,886
(SPEAKING ITALIAN)

709
00:50:45,642 --> 00:50:47,371
<i>We're not done yet.</i>

710
00:50:49,046 --> 00:50:51,037
<i>Of course we're not, darling.</i>

711
00:51:16,606 --> 00:51:17,834
(BOTH SPEAKING ITALIAN)

712
00:51:21,178 --> 00:51:22,270
Hello.

713
00:51:22,612 --> 00:51:24,204
- Hello?
- Hello.

714
00:51:27,484 --> 00:51:29,884
Hi. Is Claire with you? No?

715
00:51:30,287 --> 00:51:32,585
<i>No, no. She's turned in early, actually.</i>

716
00:51:32,656 --> 00:51:33,884
Okay.

717
00:51:33,957 --> 00:51:35,857
I was gonna ask if you wanted dinner, but...

718
00:51:35,926 --> 00:51:38,520
I just... I wanted to get started on my story.

719
00:51:39,062 --> 00:51:40,359
<i>How's it coming?</i>

720
00:51:40,430 --> 00:51:42,330
<i>It's coming okay.</i>

721
00:51:43,366 --> 00:51:44,765
Am I in it?

722
00:51:44,835 --> 00:51:47,201
- You may be. Why?
- Can I read just a little bit?

723
00:51:47,270 --> 00:51:49,534
- Are you kidding me?
- Come on, just a little bit.

724
00:51:49,606 --> 00:51:51,130
Absolutely not.

725
00:51:52,109 --> 00:51:54,771
<i>How am I to be sure that
I'm being properly portrayed?</i>

726
00:51:54,845 --> 00:51:57,143
No, you are. Believe me. You are.

727
00:51:57,214 --> 00:52:00,183
<i>- What's that supposed to mean?
- It means good night, Charlie.</i>

728
00:52:02,886 --> 00:52:04,820
- Good night.
- Okay.

729
00:52:05,989 --> 00:52:07,081
Yeah.

730
00:52:10,527 --> 00:52:11,858
Good night.

731
00:52:15,866 --> 00:52:17,561
- What? Okay.
- Is this

732
00:52:19,169 --> 00:52:22,036
<i>one of those situations
where you're really saying the opposite</i>

733
00:52:22,105 --> 00:52:24,164
of what you actually mean?

734
00:52:24,875 --> 00:52:25,899
No.

735
00:52:26,276 --> 00:52:27,436
Right.

736
00:52:28,211 --> 00:52:29,576
Good night then.

737
00:52:29,646 --> 00:52:31,341
Good night, Charlie.

738
00:52:48,398 --> 00:52:49,865
Good morning.

739
00:52:50,133 --> 00:52:51,566
Good morning.

740
00:52:51,635 --> 00:52:53,364
Gran wants to sleep in this morning.

741
00:52:53,436 --> 00:52:55,904
Is she okay?
I mean, does she need anything?

742
00:52:55,972 --> 00:52:59,100
<i>No need.
She's tough as old boots, that one.</i>

743
00:52:59,442 --> 00:53:01,239
Churchill in a dress.

744
00:53:03,613 --> 00:53:06,878
<i>So, I thought I'd see a bit of Siena
since we're here.</i>

745
00:53:06,950 --> 00:53:08,577
<i>It's a good idea.</i>

746
00:53:09,753 --> 00:53:12,415
I suppose you want to keep on writing.

747
00:53:13,723 --> 00:53:14,951
I mean...

748
00:53:15,926 --> 00:53:17,553
Work, work, work.

749
00:53:18,028 --> 00:53:19,586
Admirable trait.

750
00:53:22,966 --> 00:53:25,332
Right, of course. Carry on then.

751
00:53:28,038 --> 00:53:29,300
Charlie?

752
00:53:32,209 --> 00:53:33,972
<i>Since we're here...</i>

753
00:53:36,346 --> 00:53:40,680
<i>I hate to compliment you, but what
you're doing for Claire is really...</i>

754
00:53:41,151 --> 00:53:42,948
<i>It's sweet, and I...</i>

755
00:53:43,620 --> 00:53:47,351
<i>I imagine that you'd rather be spending
your holiday elsewhere,</i>

756
00:53:47,991 --> 00:53:52,121
so did you volunteer your services, or did
your parents? I mean, where do they fit in?

757
00:53:54,564 --> 00:53:57,624
<i>I'd like to think they're someplace nice.</i>

758
00:54:00,770 --> 00:54:03,898
They were killed in a car accident
when I was 10.

759
00:54:07,577 --> 00:54:08,908
<i>I'm sorry.</i>

760
00:54:10,780 --> 00:54:12,270
<i>God, I'm sorry.</i>

761
00:54:13,783 --> 00:54:16,274
CHARLIE: Thank you, Sophie. I appreciate it.

762
00:54:17,354 --> 00:54:19,288
It was a difficult time.

763
00:54:20,657 --> 00:54:22,318
Gran lost her son.

764
00:54:23,126 --> 00:54:24,821
I lost my parents.

765
00:54:26,529 --> 00:54:29,828
<i>I'm not a big believer in happy endings,
I'm afraid.</i>

766
00:54:31,067 --> 00:54:36,095
Anyway, Gran stepped in. Took an angry,
obnoxious, young boy under her wing

767
00:54:36,640 --> 00:54:39,837
and made me the simply unpleasant man
I am today.

768
00:54:40,543 --> 00:54:41,874
(BELL TOLLING)

769
00:54:43,179 --> 00:54:46,114
<i>CHARLIE: So, isn't your fiancé
starting to get just a tad Ionely?</i>

770
00:54:46,182 --> 00:54:49,345
<i>SOPHIE: You know, Victor's having
the time of his life right now.</i>

771
00:54:49,419 --> 00:54:52,149
<i>And I doubt he even notices that I'm gone.</i>

772
00:54:52,222 --> 00:54:53,780
What about you?

773
00:54:54,190 --> 00:54:58,593
<i>- Don't you have a girlfriend?
- That is a very, very long story.</i>

774
00:54:58,928 --> 00:55:00,418
<i>Yeah? I'm not surprised.</i>

775
00:55:00,497 --> 00:55:02,931
<i>It's been about a year
since I've seen Patricia.</i>

776
00:55:02,999 --> 00:55:04,990
And you broke up with her?

777
00:55:07,070 --> 00:55:11,404
<i>Are you insinuating that I'm more the type
to be dumped rather than do the dumping?</i>

778
00:55:11,474 --> 00:55:12,498
Maybe I am.

779
00:55:12,575 --> 00:55:15,510
Actually, I did break up with Patricia.
This time.

780
00:55:24,921 --> 00:55:26,650
<i>Okay, that's enough.</i>

781
00:55:31,828 --> 00:55:33,625
<i>All right. That's enough.</i>

782
00:55:35,532 --> 00:55:37,523
<i>- Sophie...
- That's enough.</i>

783
00:55:38,101 --> 00:55:40,934
- Your writing is really good.
- Thank you.

784
00:55:41,004 --> 00:55:43,632
<i>No. It's really, really, really good.</i>

785
00:55:44,974 --> 00:55:46,999
Why are you so surprised?

786
00:55:47,577 --> 00:55:49,670
<i>How come you've never shown
your work to anyone?</i>

787
00:55:49,746 --> 00:55:52,010
<i>- I never feel like it's finished.
- Why?</i>

788
00:55:52,082 --> 00:55:54,607
<i>Because I guess I'm a perfectionist.</i>

789
00:55:55,151 --> 00:55:58,314
<i>You know that's just another way
of saying "I'm a chicken"?</i>

790
00:55:58,388 --> 00:56:01,323
<i>Listen. You've got nothing to be afraid of.</i>

791
00:56:01,758 --> 00:56:04,454
<i>You're not a fact checker. You're a writer.</i>

792
00:56:05,829 --> 00:56:06,853
(BOTH LAUGHING)

793
00:56:06,930 --> 00:56:09,455
<i>- What was that for?
- I'm not a chicken.</i>

794
00:56:11,568 --> 00:56:13,536
<i>- And I'm not a gentleman.
- (EXCLAIMS)</i>

795
00:56:14,938 --> 00:56:16,997
Do you think we should get back to Claire?

796
00:56:17,073 --> 00:56:19,200
Yeah. Many more Lorenzos.

797
00:56:21,010 --> 00:56:22,136
Okay.

798
00:56:26,316 --> 00:56:28,375
We should get back to Claire.
(GIGGLES)

799
00:56:30,720 --> 00:56:33,052
I am Lorenzo Bartolini!

800
00:56:38,695 --> 00:56:41,220
Take him! Take him!

801
00:56:41,531 --> 00:56:43,556
I am Lorenzo Bartolini!

802
00:56:44,100 --> 00:56:46,159
I am Lorenzo Bartolini!

803
00:56:46,536 --> 00:56:47,594
Wow.

804
00:56:49,038 --> 00:56:50,835
I am Lorenzo Bartolini!

805
00:56:50,907 --> 00:56:52,101
(LAUGHING)

806
00:56:54,911 --> 00:56:56,378
(ALL LAUGHING)

807
00:56:57,180 --> 00:56:58,841
Do you know what you are?

808
00:56:58,915 --> 00:57:01,042
You are the Montagues and the Capulets.

809
00:57:01,117 --> 00:57:06,282
<i>You mean... Well, at least I'm not Romeo.</i>

810
00:57:06,556 --> 00:57:10,287
<i>- That's the understatement of the century.
- No, no, no, because you see,</i>

811
00:57:11,261 --> 00:57:14,719
<i>if I found the love of my life,
I wouldn't stand there like an idiot</i>

812
00:57:14,798 --> 00:57:16,789
whispering in a garden.

813
00:57:17,367 --> 00:57:21,565
I would just grab her from that
blasted balcony and be done with it.

814
00:57:25,508 --> 00:57:27,533
Do you believe in destiny?

815
00:57:28,711 --> 00:57:29,871
Do you?

816
00:57:30,713 --> 00:57:32,305
Yeah, I think so.

817
00:57:32,649 --> 00:57:35,709
<i>I think it's destiny that I'm here, right now.</i>

818
00:57:41,124 --> 00:57:42,523
With Claire. (CHUCKLES NERVOUSLY)

819
00:57:43,760 --> 00:57:46,126
Of course. Of course. With Claire.

820
00:58:19,629 --> 00:58:21,620
Well, this is the street.

821
00:58:25,502 --> 00:58:28,096
<i>Well, there's 2. Here's number 2.</i>

822
00:58:31,808 --> 00:58:33,241
(DOORBELL RINGS)

823
00:58:48,658 --> 00:58:54,790
(ALL SPEAKING ITALIAN)

824
00:59:03,573 --> 00:59:04,801
(HONKING)

825
00:59:45,882 --> 00:59:47,315
This is what I feared the most.

826
00:59:47,383 --> 00:59:51,149
<i>- Charlie, we don't even know if it's him.
- I hope it's not. I hope it's not.</i>

827
00:59:51,788 --> 00:59:54,814
<i>- Either way, we're finished. We're done.
- No. Not here.</i>

828
00:59:55,458 --> 00:59:57,050
When do we stop?

829
00:59:57,794 --> 01:00:00,262
Over the next hill? Or the next?
Scour the whole country?

830
01:00:00,330 --> 01:00:01,991
No. No. It ends here.

831
01:00:02,065 --> 01:00:05,159
There are other Lorenzos
not too far away from here.

832
01:00:05,234 --> 01:00:07,794
<i>It's not the ending you want, is it?</i>

833
01:00:08,438 --> 01:00:09,962
<i>This isn't just a clever story</i>

834
01:00:10,039 --> 01:00:11,506
- with a clever ending.
- Stop it, Charlie.

835
01:00:11,574 --> 01:00:13,371
<i>- It's our life. It's my Gran's life.
- It's not about...</i>

836
01:00:13,443 --> 01:00:14,910
<i>Charlie, it's not about a story.</i>

837
01:00:14,978 --> 01:00:17,469
<i>No, no, no, she's already lost the man once.</i>

838
01:00:19,048 --> 01:00:21,676
How many more times
would you have her lose him?

839
01:00:22,385 --> 01:00:24,478
<i>You know what?
I don't expect you to understand any of this</i>

840
01:00:24,554 --> 01:00:27,580
<i>because you don't know a thing
about real loss.</i>

841
01:00:28,825 --> 01:00:29,951
Yeah.

842
01:00:43,573 --> 01:00:45,040
<i>You're wrong.</i>

843
01:00:47,910 --> 01:00:51,710
<i>Sophie's mother ran away from her
when she was a little girl.</i>

844
01:00:55,084 --> 01:00:58,212
<i>It's different, Gran. It's different.</i>

845
01:01:03,259 --> 01:01:04,749
<i>You're right.</i>

846
01:01:06,229 --> 01:01:07,355
But

847
01:01:11,234 --> 01:01:13,896
<i>Sophie's mother chose to leave her.</i>

848
01:01:14,904 --> 01:01:17,737
And you always knew your mum and dad
loved you.

849
01:01:37,126 --> 01:01:38,650
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

850
01:01:38,728 --> 01:01:39,990
Come in.

851
01:01:44,600 --> 01:01:45,624
Hi.

852
01:01:57,280 --> 01:01:58,611
Oh, dear.

853
01:02:03,753 --> 01:02:06,551
I just wanted to see if you were all right.

854
01:02:06,622 --> 01:02:07,850
<i>I'm okay.</i>

855
01:02:15,965 --> 01:02:18,433
<i>Claire, I'm so sorry if I caused you...</i>

856
01:02:18,501 --> 01:02:19,593
No.

857
01:02:20,002 --> 01:02:22,800
Every minute has been so special.

858
01:02:27,944 --> 01:02:29,309
Darling.

859
01:02:52,168 --> 01:02:53,362
May I?

860
01:03:03,146 --> 01:03:07,480
<i>One of the great joys in life
is having one's hair brushed.</i>

861
01:03:23,866 --> 01:03:25,925
<i>CLAIRE: Charlie, say you're sorry.</i>

862
01:03:28,104 --> 01:03:31,733
In the eye, Charlie. With contrition.

863
01:03:39,148 --> 01:03:40,445
Sophie...

864
01:03:41,117 --> 01:03:42,209
<i>- Thank you.
...I'm afraid I...</i>

865
01:03:42,285 --> 01:03:43,684
In the eye.

866
01:03:44,487 --> 01:03:46,387
<i>Yes, Gran, I'm not 12.</i>

867
01:03:48,391 --> 01:03:49,619
Prove it.

868
01:03:58,734 --> 01:04:01,669
<i>I'm sincerely sorry, Sophie.</i>

869
01:04:06,442 --> 01:04:08,000
<i>It won't happen again.</i>

870
01:04:08,945 --> 01:04:10,276
Excellent.

871
01:04:13,382 --> 01:04:14,542
CLAIRE: Sophie,

872
01:04:15,051 --> 01:04:17,542
- I want to make a toast.
- Thank you.

873
01:04:17,920 --> 01:04:23,324
I want to thank you for the wonderful thing
you did for a complete stranger.

874
01:04:23,392 --> 01:04:25,223
<i>I'll never forget it.</i>

875
01:04:25,728 --> 01:04:26,752
Nor I.

876
01:04:26,829 --> 01:04:31,027
<i>I've had the most incredible few days.
I really have,</i>

877
01:04:31,934 --> 01:04:34,164
<i>and I can't thank you enough
for letting me tag along.</i>

878
01:04:34,237 --> 01:04:37,104
I think you did more than tag along.

879
01:04:37,640 --> 01:04:41,940
Here is to all our loved ones,
wherever they may be.

880
01:05:01,797 --> 01:05:03,287
May I join you?

881
01:05:03,366 --> 01:05:04,594
Please.

882
01:05:15,344 --> 01:05:17,073
I am sorry, Sophie.

883
01:05:24,787 --> 01:05:28,621
I used to lay out under the stars as a kid,
in the summertime.

884
01:05:31,560 --> 01:05:34,825
<i>"Doubt thou the stars are fire</i>

885
01:05:35,331 --> 01:05:37,561
<i>"Doubt that the sun doth move"</i>

886
01:05:39,101 --> 01:05:41,001
<i>CHARLIE: "Doubt truth be a liar</i>

887
01:05:42,038 --> 01:05:44,006
<i>"But never doubt I love"</i>

888
01:05:51,547 --> 01:05:54,277
<i>Do you think he's out there? Lorenzo?</i>

889
01:05:54,583 --> 01:05:55,709
Yeah.

890
01:05:57,520 --> 01:05:59,044
<i>He's somewhere.</i>

891
01:06:01,791 --> 01:06:04,282
And am I wrong? To insist she quit?

892
01:06:05,795 --> 01:06:07,262
No, you know,

893
01:06:09,165 --> 01:06:11,099
<i>you can't go on forever.</i>

894
01:06:11,534 --> 01:06:13,832
At some point, you have to stop.

895
01:06:16,005 --> 01:06:19,372
Then why is it that
I feel like a schoolboy on Sunday?

896
01:06:23,079 --> 01:06:25,604
<i>It's nearly tomorrow and I don't want to go.</i>

897
01:06:27,850 --> 01:06:29,249
Me, either.

898
01:06:30,953 --> 01:06:33,012
And I always liked school.

899
01:07:41,457 --> 01:07:43,118
- Morning.
- Morning.

900
01:07:43,492 --> 01:07:44,550
Thank you.

901
01:07:44,627 --> 01:07:45,924
<i>How'd you sleep?</i>

902
01:07:45,995 --> 01:07:48,020
I slept fine. How about you?

903
01:07:48,464 --> 01:07:50,659
Yes. Great. Thanks.

904
01:07:55,671 --> 01:07:57,639
CHARLIE: Good morning.
CLAIRE: Good morning.

905
01:07:58,441 --> 01:08:00,534
- How are you?
- Good morning, my darling.

906
01:08:01,377 --> 01:08:03,208
<i>It's a beautiful day.</i>

907
01:08:07,383 --> 01:08:12,685
<i>Sophie, would you mind going in the front?
Because I'd love to stretch my legs for a bit.</i>

908
01:08:15,224 --> 01:08:16,316
Okay.

909
01:08:18,961 --> 01:08:20,656
Fantastic, darling.

910
01:08:24,133 --> 01:08:26,931
CLAIRE: The stars were spectacular
from my window.

911
01:08:31,207 --> 01:08:33,607
(SINGING IN ITALIAN)

912
01:08:45,221 --> 01:08:49,749
<i>Look. That vineyard.
That's our favorite wine.</i>

913
01:08:49,825 --> 01:08:54,125
<i>Let's turn in there
and have a goodbye toast.</i>

914
01:08:54,196 --> 01:08:55,288
Okay.

915
01:09:17,620 --> 01:09:19,178
Charlie, stop!

916
01:09:35,137 --> 01:09:36,764
CHARLIE: Nana, what is it?

917
01:09:39,608 --> 01:09:41,075
<i>It's Lorenzo.</i>

918
01:09:43,312 --> 01:09:44,404
